The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, April 06, 2004 				 Allahabad Bank sees net profit at Rs 300 cr
 A STAFF REPORTER																								Calcutta, April 5: Allahabad Bank is set to unveil a net profit of over Rs 300 crore and an operating profit in excess of Rs 700 crore in the financial year that ended in March, according to chairman . . Singh.																								In the first nine months of the financial year, the bank had posted a net profit of Rs 242.23 crore. 																								Net profit of Rs 300 crore translates into earning per share (EPS) of Rs 8.65  Rs 5.89 in the previous year.																								Our target for 2003-04 was (a net profit of) Rs 300 crore. We have achieved it, Singh said.																								Analysts are expecting the bank to announce a net profit of around Rs 350 crore, which translates into an earning per share of Rs 10.10.																								The bank expects its net profit to grow over 60 per cent in 2004-05 to Rs 500 crore, while operating profit is projected to top Rs 1,000 crore.																								The bank is working on its targets for the next year. The figures that the chairman mentioned are ballpark estimates.																								Allahabad Banks shares closed 75 paise higher at Rs 33.20 on the Bombay Stock Exchange today.																								In a statement made to stock exchanges recently, the bank said its total business volume (deposits plus advances) was expected to cross Rs 47,000 crore in 2003-04, and top Rs 60,000 crore in 2004-05. 																								The bank is aiming to cut its net non-performing loans from 4 per cent of assets to 1 per cent by March 2005.																								The bank is on aggressive expansion mode. Its chairman said recently, the management was considering acquisition of a bank in the south. Allahabad Bank has also applied for Reserve Banks approval to set up two overseas branches in South East Asia.
